english:
  title: Reply to a Letter
  author: Kim Jong-jik
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your second letter has come, and I see in it the seeds of remorse and awakening. When one can correct one's faults, even the sage approves—how much more so between you and me? If you truly can repent, how could I ever bar the way to your renewal? When I rebuked you before, I pressed too urgently, causing you to falter and stumble, your words tumbling forth before your mind could settle. That was my fault—how could I truly harbor lasting anger toward you?

    Alas, when your grandfather passed, your father became the chief mourner, and I followed by dwelling in the mourning house. Now that your grandmother has passed, you are the chief mourner, and I again dwell in grief beside you. In these twenty-five years, father and son of your line have rested upon straw mats in this mountain together with me. What is this but the way of the world? This is why my heart clings to you and longs for your swift return.

    Yet what weighs upon me, cutting deep and unbearable, goes beyond this alone. When you are here, I follow you in the evening offerings; when visitors come to mourn, I follow you. When I sit alone, people suspect me of being the chief mourner—unthinkable! To leave the mourning house vacant—also impossible! When guests arrive and ask of your whereabouts, though I tell them you tend to your widowed mother's illness, once or twice suffices. But when they return a fourth or fifth time and ask again, how can I explain away the doubt that stirs within? You are young with a long road ahead. One failure in conduct brings countless reproaches. How can you not consider this? And there is something weightier still.

    Our clan has flourished for more than a hundred years since the time of Hwa-ui. Many descendants have come forth since Lord Yangon's generation, yet none rose to positions of minister or duke. Those who passed the examinations were but four: my father, my father's cousin Jong-ri, your father, and myself. Alas, a hundred years have passed, and only four gained advancement—our house accounts for three of them! Last year, your cousin Kang also succeeded in the highest examination. This too springs from our family's learning. From this we can see that the accumulated merit of our ancestors is blossoming in our line.

    When I named you and your cousins in years past, I gave you all names with the silk radical, hoping you would inherit and perpetuate our family's legacy without end. Su and Hong—my second cousin instructs them, and they will surely achieve greatness. I have but one son, now useless through illness, with no hope of teaching him further. Yet you two have already shown your mettle, standing above your peers! Still, your learning lacks breadth and depth. You have barely escaped the trap of outward cleverness, yet the true craft remains unfinished. If you grow slack in study and cultivation, time will slip away. What then?

    Though my virtue is meager and my learning shameful, since taking office I have received the gracious favor of the throne, never leaving the golden halls of service. Thus, even withdrawn in these mountains, when scholars from distant lands occasionally come seeking learning, I forget my sorrow in discourse with them. I am guilty before the Way of Names and Righteousness, yet I do not refuse their footsteps. If you could remain at my side morning and evening, and in the hours between reading the rites, seek what you do not yet know—learning broadly, questioning carefully, thinking deeply, and discerning clearly—you would lay the foundation for sincere practice in days to come. In three years, the chaff would ripen into grain, and you would not tarnish the thread our ancestors left behind. Is this not worthy? Those who come bearing their books from afar, traveling with blistered feet, could not accomplish half of what you might achieve here.

    This is why I beg you to cast off worldly burdens and return swiftly.

    Alas, in this age there is no one like your father. He possessed filial piety, brotherly love, loyalty, and sincerity by nature. In the old days at Goryeong, when your grandfather lay ill with a painful sore, I tended his bedside. One day we tried earthworm juice. Young and unknowing of its bitter taste, I sipped it once by chance. Your father mistook this as a sign of kindred spirit and showed me unfailing affection throughout his life. How sad! Now, though I would drink of that bitter remedy again, how could I ever obtain it? Here we dwelled together for three years in mourning. In the depths of night, startled awake, I hear still his earnest voice echoing in my ears. When my thoughts reach this point, my heart tears asunder.

    Your father is gone, yet his legacy remains in you two. My deepest wish is to guide you toward greatness and see you honored in the world. Do not, I beg you, let my former rebukes embitter you against me. If your wife and children lack a home to return to, wait until the dwelling is completed and then come—there is no rush. Yet know this: Master Zhu said, "When a gentleman builds a house, he first establishes the ancestral shrine to the east of the main chamber." This stands at the head of the Family Rituals. Do you understand? I cannot say more.
